2 Introduction

This chapter will introduce basic concepts in regular expressions through using a case study. The regular expression theory in this course is largely language agnostic, in that all major programming language implement them in a similar manner.

The beginning of the course will be conducted using a website tool, regex101.com that helps us easily test expressions. Later on, we will look at how to use regular expressions in python and with data sets in pandas.

Note - regegex101 may let you only select python version 2.7 - this will not impact your learning of regex, and what you learn will be transferable.

3 Learning Outcomes

By the end of the module you will: * Be able to understand when regular expressions are useful

  • Be able to write expressions that use:
    • Characters
    • Multiple characters
    • Unknown characters
    • Special character
    • Groups of expressions
    • Starting and ending characters
  • Be able to write expressions using combinations of the above.

Additionally you should be able to:

  • Use regular expressions in python with the re and pandas libraries.


4 Regular expressions

Regular expressions are a useful tool when we have text data.

Often when using text data we want to find out if the text meets some criteria.

Some example things we might want to check the text data for:

  • if text starts with the letter âBâ
  • if all the letters in the text are capitalised
  • if the text ends in a question mark â?â
  • whether the text contains a specific keyword, like a name or location

These checks can mostly be done using our programming knowledge about strings and looping through the data. To check for the starting letter in a text we can check the first element, we can loop over all text and check if each letter is capitalised, and so on.

However, there are more complicated checks we may need to make on our text data. These are going to be harder to do by indexing and looping though the data.

Some harder tasks to achieve are checking: * whether the text is a valid email * if a password meets some security requirement * whether a phone number follows a valid format * if a mistake has been made when inputting some data manually

Using this password security example, we may use regex to specify four security requirements:

  1. Must contain at least one uppercase letter.
  2. Must contain at least one lowercase letter.
  3. Must have at least one digit.
  4. Must be longer than 7 characters.

To check a given password for this criteria we would need to program a very specific solution such as: * loop over every element and check whether each is uppercase or lowercase, passes if at least one element is of each. * loop through the text and check if each element is a digit, if at least one is pass the criteria. * count the number of elements in the string, if the length is greater than 7 pass the criteria.

Itâs clear that there is going to be some iteration and potentially a lot of conditions in the program to get it to work for our requirements.

Regular expressions allow us to tackle these problems more easily than using a typical string programming approach. They are used widely to search and replace parts of text data.

A regular expression lets us design a pattern for our specific problem. This pattern will describe what we need from the text data without needing to loop through the string ourselves, or add complex conditional statements (if/else statements).

Regular expressions in many languages are more computationally efficient than looping and conditional logic. Even when they are not as efficient, they can be significantly clearer.

The above password problem can be fully described by the following regular expression:

â^(?=.(?=.[a-z])(?=.[A-Z])(?=.[a-zA-Z]).{8,}$â

Note you do not need to understand the above yet.

The above text may be quite intimidating, but what they can do is extremely powerful. Regular expressions are a language themselves, but we are going to start small and then build up to more complicated expressions like the one above.

Below is an example of the same regular expression broken into groups, each showing what we want to match from our criteria.

6 The Case Study

Throughout this module we are going to work through a specific problem, introducing regular expression (regex) concepts as we go. The first few concepts we are going to test using the regex101.com website, after that we will bring them all together in python.

6.1 The Task

Your team is running a large conference which is only available to current civil servants. Your team has decided that it is going to check that individuals are eligible for the event by checking their registered email.

Broadly there are two things which you will need to check: * That the person enrolled has a validly formatted email. * That the email has a government domain.

Specifically, you need to check for each email: * the email follows firstname.lastname convention in the username, such as Jenny.Smith@ons.gov.uk. Each name should be letters only, no numbers or special characters. * there is an @** character between the username and email domain. * the email ends in .gov.uk. * the domain contains a department name (it doesnât need to be a real department) before the .gov.uk**, which is letters only.

You have been given the addition information: * all letters in the emails can be upper or lowercase. * the text will not contain any spaces.

6.2 Your role

While you could try and check all the email addresses by hand, or by writing a program with lots of conditional statements, you have decided to tackle this problem with regular expressions.

You have been told that the best approach to building regular expressions is to tackle each criteria of the pattern, a sub-pattern, then combine them. At each step youâre going to check the sub pattern against some realistic partial test text.

Once the expression is all brought together, there is a file containing test emails that can be used to validate whether your expression gets the matching right.

6.3 Matching Letters

The first part of the problem we are going to tackle is to check that the first name in the email contains just letters.

To do this we need two things: * To be able to match when something is a letter * To match multiple letters

6.3.1 Match a letter

We can create a âsetâ of values we want to match by using square brackets [] and putting the elements we want to match inside. [A] would mean match a single character equal to âAâ.

For example, if I wanted to match the letters a, b or c I could create the set [abc]. This will check an individual element in a string, and see if that element is a member of the set.

The set [abc] when applied to each element separately in abracadabra would give the following matches:

We will learn how to match over a whole string later.

We can create a more general set by indicating a range of values we want. For example we can:

  • match the set of all lowercase letters: [a-z]
  • match the set of all uppercase letters: [A-Z]
  • match the set of all digits: [0-9]

More strings can be included in the set to widen what it will match. For example if we want to match all lowercase letters AND spaces, we could write [a-z ], notice the space now inside the set.

6.3.1.1 Negate a set

If we want to match characters that are not in the set specified we can use the ^ character within the set.

To match anything that is not a digit we would use the set [^0-9].

6.4 Match multiple letters

We have so far matched only individual letters, or a specified string of characters. In order to be able to match a first name from our emails we are going to need to specify how many letters there could be.

To change the number of occurrences of a character in our expression we add a special character after the character we want occurring.

A special character is a character which has a particular meaning other than itself.

There are three special characters we will look at that can modify the number of occurrences of a character, these are:

  • + - preceding character appears once or more times
  • *** - preceding character appears 0 or more times
  • ? - preceding character appears 0 or 1 times
  • {n} - preceding character appears n times
  • {n,} - preceding character appears n or more times
  • {n,m} - preceding character appears n or more times, but no more than m times

These specific special characters are called Quantifiers as they determine how many times a string occurs.

By using these in combination with the characters we want we can fit the right pattern to our needs.

If we definitely know we want a character to be present, we will use the + special character.

For example, if I want to match the letter a followed by at least one h, I would use the regex ah+.

Try out ah+ in regex101.com using the below test strings:

  • ah
  • ahhhh
  • ahhhhhhh
  • a
  • h
  • ahhhhha

The strings will only match the whole first 3 strings. The last case is partially matched, but note that it doesnât pick up on the final a.

If we know that a specific character may or may not appear, we often use the ? character. This is similar to saying âthe preceding character might be there, and either way we want to match itâ.

Be careful when using occurrence that could be present zero times, it may not pick up what you want!

Note: These characters are greedy - they will match the maximum numbers of characters that they can. The alternative to greedy is lazy. Greedy matching will find the maximum number of occurrences for a match, lazy will find the minimum. We can convert any quantifier from greedy to lazy if we choose by using an addition ? character. This is beyond the depth required for this course, for more information Greedy and lazy quantifiers.

Write the following regex into regex101.com and add the below test strings c?at * cat * bat * chat * at

Add in some more words ending in at and see which match fully. In the above examples only cat and at match because due to the ? character the c may or may not be present for a match to happen.

The last special character in this area is **. This denotes that the preceding character occurs either one or many times. For this reason it is often said to denote occurs any amount of times*. It is like a combination of the two previous characters.

Write the following regex into regex101.com and add the below test strings the he * the * tttttttttttthe

As you can see the regex will fully match all three of these examples, it is very tolerant in that it will take any number of occurrences. Use it only if youâre sure your task can accept having 0 occurrences of some character.

6.4.1 Shorthand - Character Classes

In regex there are a range of shorthand characters that exist for commonly used patterns.

They are really useful for making your regex shorter, and therefore clearer. However, it is important you use the correct one for specific purposes, as they can easily be confused.

Below are a few examples, what they match and their equivalents. Remember we can find patterns not in a set using the ^ special character.

  • word character (letters and numbers): [A-z0-9_]

  • not word character (non letters and non numbers): [^A-z0-9_]

  • white space (space, newline, tab): [ \n\t]

  • not white space (not space, newline or tab): [\n\t]

  • digit (number): [0-9]

  • not digit (not a number): [^0-9]

We are now equipped to start thinking about our case study. We can now match multiple occurrences of a set of characters. If we look back at our criteria:

  • the email follows firstname . lastname convention in the username, such as Jenny.Smith@ons.gov.uk. Each name should just be letters.
  • there is an *@* character between the username and email domain
  • the email ends in .gov.uk
  • the domain contains a department name (it doesnât need to be a real department) before the .gov.uk, which is all letters.

We can start piecing together parts of our final regular expression.

To match the firstname, lastname and government department we are actually going to use the same sub expression.

What we need is to match a string of letters (one or more letter), that is possibly a mix of uppercase and lowercase.

6.6 Any Character

So far we have looked at sets, strings and multiple occurrences. These are useful, but we need to have information about the what that character will be.

To overcome this there is a special character which will match anything, no matter what character is present.

This can be a really useful addition to our tool belt as it allows us to add in a generic placeholders where we donât know what our string will look like.

In regex101 write the following regex and test text, *.**

This CAN hav3 an%thing

As you can see, this matches the whole string fully, and it will match anything we throw at it, even if we give it an empty string. Test this by adding more text strings with different punctuation and characters.

6.6.1 Escaping special characters

Introducing these special characters gives us more flexibility, but what happens if we want to match one of the special characters? For example, what if we want our expression to match a + symbol itself, not itâs special character meaning?

To do this we âescapeâ the special character by adding in a new special character: **. By putting this before the character we want to escape.

For example, to escape + we would write +. Or to escape *** we would write *. If we even wanted to escape * we can use \*.

6.6.2 Grouping Expressions

We have been writing sub-expressions so far that can be combined. It is often useful to contain our sub-expressions in groups by using the special character brackets (). This is done particularly when the sub-expression becomes complicated.

Each sub-expression gets put within a pair of brackets.

(first_expression)(second_expression)

These sub-expressions can form different groups that we can extend by nesting or creating groups with. This is beyond the scope of this course, but the ideas can be built on to capture more in depth patterns.

6.7 Starting and Ending Strings

As you can see in the previous exercise, at the moment we can still have parts of strings that do not match returning a partial match.

For example in charlie.alexander123, the 123 part goes unmatched. This could lead to unintended consequences, such as creating matches that contain extra leading or trailing strings.

This is counteracted by using two more special characters.

^ proceeds a character/expression marking the start of a string.

$ follows a character to mark that it ends the string.

For example, if we wanted an expression that matched anything as long as it starts with a capital letter and ends with a question mark, filled with anything in-between.

To match the strings starting with a capital letter use â^([A-Z])â

To match the strings ending in a question mark use â?$â

To match anything in between use â.*.

All together this becomes:

â^([A-Z])(.*)(?$)â

Copy the expression into regex101 and try it out with your own question strings.

6.8 Lookarounds

The concept of lookarounds also exist and are useful to be aware of.

These character combinations allow us to look ahead or behind in a string to check if a pattern is matching, without actually returning the value found.

We can have either positive or negative look around. They will match whether, or not, a pattern appears before or after the rest of our pattern without actually returning what is ahead or behind. This is again, beyond the scope of this course, but for more information see: this tutorial if you are interested.

Consider that we want to extract the value of a price from a website, for example.

Each price we scrape will have a Â£ sign in front of it. We only want to extract numbers that have this Â£ in front of it, but we do not actually want the Â£ to be returned in our result.

A lookahead refers to looking right, english text is read left to right. A look behind therefore looks back towards the left.

We would choose to use a positive lookbehind, in this situation. Positive because we want the expression to be there, lookbehind we are looking back towards the left of the string.

To match this described pattern we would use a regex similar to:

(?<=Â£)[0-9]+

This will return:

  • from Â£10 return 10
  • from Â£500 return 500
  • from I need Â£2 please return 2

This means we would not need to clean the resulting string!

7 Using regex in programming

So far we have been using the regex101 tool to test the regular expressions we have designed. This is a great tool for learning, and testing individual expressions, but at some point we need to use the expressions in our programming itself.

Regular expressions are supported in many programming major languages, including python, R, Unix and windows command line interfaces.

Occasionally there are slight differences in how the languages style their regular expression, these differences are minor.

In python there is a library included called re which gives the programmer access to regular expressions and related functions. In addition, to use regular expressions in dataframes pandas provides a range of string methods which take regular expressions as inputs.

In R there is a package included called grep which allows the programmer to use regular expressions with text data. Within the tidyverse the stringr package has functions that can use regular expressions.

This is a Python tutorial, so we will focus on how to use regex using python packages.

7.1 The re library

The re library, short for regular expressions, contains a range of functions that allow us to use regular expressions in text. We are going to show two frequently used operations: searching and substituting.

7.1.1 Searching

# Import the package to use it's functions
import re

# Define a string we are going to work with
search_text = "Mary had a little lamb."

# Define a regex to matching a string starting with "Mary", 
# it can have anything after, but ends in "little"
mary_regex = "^(Mary).*(little)"

# Run the search function using the expression and string
match_object = re.search(pattern=mary_regex, string=search_text)
# The match object found contains all we need from our regex search
match_object

We can access each piece of information individually

# The group() gives us the string that matches the regex
match_object.group()
# The string gives us the original string that was given to the search function
match_object.string
# The span() tells us which indexes the regex matches in the string
match_object.span()

There is also a function to re.findall() function, which will return all non-overlapping strings in a string that match the given regex expression. It is called in a similar manner to re.search().

7.1.2 Substituting

To substitute we need to define: * The regular expression stating what we want to match * The string we want to replace the match with * The string we want searched

# Define a string we are going to work with
original_text = "The      porridge   in the  hotel     was    too hot"

# Define a regex to match the "hot" at the end of the string,
# but not in "hotel"
temperature_regex = "hot$"

# Run the search function using the expression and string
new_text = re.sub(pattern=temperature_regex, repl="cold", string=original_text)

new_text
# Find all spaces
extra_spaces_regex = " +"

# Replace single or multiple spaces with a single space
no_spaces_text = re.sub(pattern=extra_spaces_regex, repl=" ", string=new_text)

no_spaces_text

7.1.3 Matching

Following on from searching and substituting, you can also use re.match() to determine whether or not a given string matches your expression. This produces a match object in a similar way to re.search().

7.1.4 Using regex with pandas

Pandas contains a range of string based methods in the .str group, such as .startswith(), .replace() and .lower().

Just like with re we can match and substitute using regular expressions using string data in pandas columns.

This is done using the .str.match(pat=regex) method for matching and .str.replace(pat=regex, repl=replacement, regex=True) to substituting on the columns we want to operate on.

The matching method will provide us with a Series of True/False values, depending on whether the string in each row matches the expression (pat) given.

The replace method will return a new column where the string in each row has had any matching sub string replaced.

7.2 Testing our regex

Below we are going to import a dataset that contains (fake) emails which may or may not meet the specified criteria to be eligible for signing up to the event. 7.3 Summary

Using regular expressions we can match complex patterns in strings. This is done by using âspecial charactersâ in the regex languages. Each of these characters has a meaning, which when combined can describe a pattern of text.

The expressions will allow us to match and substitute with more flexibility and efficiency than traditional programming methods.

We have covered the following regular expression concepts: * Matching strings * Sets * Multiple occurrences * The . character * Expression grouping * Beginning and ending strings

In addition, we have briefly looked at using these concepts in python with: * The re library * pandas * Matching and substituting * A case study

From here you should be able to build some of your own regular expressions to solve string based problems. Remember, it is crucial that you apply your expressions to test strings to check that the expression performs as intended.

This tutorial covered a sub-set of special characters in regex, for more on special characters, please look at the links in Further Reading.
